# Website Semantic Color Token Discipline

Applies when authoring or reviewing website UI that resolves colors through `semanticColor` (`website/src/resources/configs/utils.ts`) and `ThemeMap` (`website/src/resources/configs/theme.ts`). Authority: `docs/platforms/website/brand-identity-alignment.md`, W43.

## Non-negotiables

1. **Prefer `semanticColor.<key>` over `@white` / `@<BaseColor>` hardcodes** whenever a semantic token exists. A hardcoded `@white` on a primary/navy control must be `semanticColor.primaryActionText`; a hardcoded `@white` on an accent control must be `semanticColor.accentActionText`.
2. **Pair text/icon color against the resolved surface fill, not against the page color scheme.** White text is valid on a primary/dark fill and wrong on a light fill. Before writing `clr`/`color`, resolve `bg` to its `ThemeMap` leaf value in the active scheme and confirm contrast. The same pairing applies to **SVG** `fill` / `stroke` resolved via `getColor(semanticColor.…)`: glyphs drawn on a scheme-flipped surface (`cardBackground`, page, etc.) must use content tokens (`textPrimary` / `textSecondary` / `iconPrimary`), **not** action fills like `primaryActionBackground` (navy stays dark in light **and** dark → near-invisible on a dark card).
3. **`theme.ts` is brand authority — do not edit it to satisfy a consumer.** If a token seems missing, first check whether an existing `semanticColor` key already covers the case; only add a new key when a real consumer needs it (YAGNI — no dead tokens).
4. **Path validity is type-guarded.** `semanticColor` entries are typed `as ColorType`, and `ColorType` includes `ThemeMapPath` (a string-literal union derived from `ThemeMapType` via `FullNestedPaths`). `yarn type-check` (`tsc --noEmit`) rejects any path string that is not a real `ThemeMap` leaf. A passing `type-check` is proof that all `semanticColor` paths resolve.

## Forbidden

- `@white` / `@<BaseColor>` literals where a `semanticColor` action-text/icon token already expresses the intent.
- Pairing `textInverted` (white) with a light surface such as `secondaryActionBackground` (navy[50]) — invisible text.
- Using `primaryActionBackground` / other fixed-dark action fills as SVG text `fill` on `cardBackground` (or any scheme-flipped surface).
- Adding `semanticColor` tokens for hypothetical future consumers (dead code).
- Editing `theme.ts` to work around a consumer contrast bug — fix the consumer pairing instead.
- Bypassing the `ThemeMapPath` guard with `as any` / `as string` to silence a path error — the error means the path is wrong.

## Canonical cases

- `FormActionButton.tsx`: primary text = `semanticColor.primaryActionText` over `semanticColor.primaryActionBackground` (navy); neutral text = `semanticColor.textPrimary` over `semanticColor.cardBackground`.
- `HomeFocusVisual.tsx`: hub percent SVG `fill` = `getColor(semanticColor.textPrimary)` over hub `cardBackground`; seat strokes may still use navy/`primaryActionBackground`.
- `ThemeModeSwitch.tsx`: single toggle button — icon `semanticColor.iconPrimary` over `semanticColor.inputBackground` (with `inputBorder`, corner `semanticDims.card.radius`); icon shows the **target** mode (`FiMoon` when light, `FiSun` when dark), click toggles to that scheme.
- `LanguageSwitch.tsx`: single toggle button — text `semanticColor.iconPrimary` (bold) over `semanticColor.inputBackground` (with `inputBorder`, corner `semanticDims.card.radius`); label shows the **target** language (`EN` when ar, `ع` when en), click calls `changeLocale` to switch.
- `Header.tsx` `HeaderIconButton`: icon `semanticColor.iconPrimary` over `semanticColor.inputBackground` (with `inputBorder`, corner `semanticDims.card.radius`) — menu / back / trailing action (notifications).
- `UiMockup.tsx` status badge `reviewed`: `bg = semanticColor.secondaryActionBackground` (navy[50]) pairs with `clr = semanticColor.secondaryActionText` (navy).
- `LandingFooter.tsx` / `Footer.tsx`: `bg = semanticColor.footerBackground` is **theme-flipped** (`NeutralColors[100]` light / `#040811` dark — W56), so text MUST be the theme-flipped `semanticColor.textPrimary` (links) and `semanticColor.textAccent` (titles), NOT a fixed-light token. This is the inverse of the fixed-fill controls above: the footer surface follows the scheme, so the text must follow it too.

## Exemptions

- **Third-party brand colors** (W57): a hardcoded hex that reproduces an EXTERNAL brand identity (e.g. `MicrobandCredit.tsx` **MicroBand** blue `#096fb1`) is exempt from non-negotiable #1. The brand owns the value; do not replace it with a `semanticColor` token, do not add a `semanticColor` entry for it (YAGNI + brand-authority), and do not "fix" it for dark-mode contrast. If a third-party brand color reads poorly on a themed Ejtmaa surface, change the Ejtmaa surface, never the brand color. This exemption is narrow: it covers only verbatim external brand wordmark/logo colors, not Ejtmaa's own UI accents. The linked wordmark text MUST stay spelled **`MicroBand`** via `ui.components.microbandCredit.brand`.

## Audit procedure

To re-verify alignment after any `theme.ts` or `semanticColor` change, run the audit in `.cursor/skills/website-semantic-color-audit/SKILL.md` (consumer inventory + 52-key line map + `yarn type-check`).

